[101.005327, "o", "                                                         \u001b[1;4mClick Framework Onboarding Document\u001b[0m                                                          \r\n\r\n\u001b[4;35mWhat this repo actually does\u001b[0m                                                                                                                          \r\n\r\nClick is a Python library for creating command-line interfaces (CLIs). It provides decorators and utilities to transform regular Python functions into\r\nCLI commands with automatic argument parsing, option handling, validation, and help generation. The library follows a decorator-based approach where  \r\nyou annotate functions with \u001b[1;36;40m@click.command()\u001b[0m and \u001b[1;36;40m@click.option()\u001b[0m to define CLI behavior.                                                              \r\n\r\n\u001b[4;35mHow to run it locally\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                 \r\n\r\nBased on the source code structure, this is a library package, not a standalone application. To work with it locally:                                 \r\n\r\n\u001b[36m 1 \u001b[0mClone the repository                                                                                                                               \r\n\u001b[36m 2 \u001b[0mInstall in development mode: \u001b[1;36;40mpip install -e .\u001b[0m                                                                                                      \r\n\u001b[36m 3 \u001b[0mRun examples: \u001b[1;36;40mpython examples/validation/validation.py --help\u001b[0m                                                                                      \r\n\u001b[36m 4 \u001b[0mRun tests: \u001b[1;36;40mpython -m pytest tests/\u001b[0m (standard Python testing)                                                                                       \r\n\u001b[36m 5 \u001b[0mFor complex examples: \u001b[1;36;40mcd examples/complex && python -m complex.cli --help\u001b[0m                                                                          \r\n\r\n\u001b[4;35mArchitecture: how the pieces connect\u001b[0m                                                                                                                  \r\n\r\n\u001b[1mCore Flow:\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                            \r\n\r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40m@click.command()\u001b[0m decorator converts functions into \u001b[1;36;40mCommand\u001b[0m objects                                                                                 \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40m@click.option()\u001b[0m and \u001b[1;36;40m@click.argument()\u001b[0m decorators add parameters                                                                                    \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40mContext\u001b[0m objects carry state through command execution                                                                                              \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40mGroup\u001b[0m classes organize multiple commands into CLI applications                                                                                     \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0mParameter types handle validation and conversion                                                                                                   \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0mBuilt-in integration with environment variables and configuration                                                                                  \r\n\r\n\u001b[1mKey Components:\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                       \r\n\r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mCommands\u001b[0m: Individual CLI operations (functions decorated with \u001b[1;36;40m@click.command()\u001b[0m)                                                                    \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mGroups\u001b[0m: Collections of commands (like git's subcommands)                                                                                           \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mParameters\u001b[0m: Options (\u001b[1;36;40m--flag\u001b[0m) and arguments (positional values)                                                                                     \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mContext\u001b[0m: Execution state passed between commands                                                                                                   \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mTypes\u001b[0m: Parameter validation and conversion system                                                                                                  \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mDecorators\u001b[0m: The primary API surface (\u001b[1;36;40m@click.option\u001b[0m, \u001b[1;36;40m@click.argument\u001b[0m, etc.)                                                                         \r\n\r\n\u001b[4;35mCore files to read first (with one-line explanations)\u001b[0m                                                                                                 \r\n\r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40msrc/click/core.py\u001b[0m - Main classes: Command, Group, Option, Argument, Context                                                                        \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40msrc/click/decorators.py\u001b[0m - Primary API decorators (@click.command, @click.option, etc.)                                                             \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40msrc/click/types.py\u001b[0m - Parameter type system for validation and conversion                                                                           \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40msrc/click/parser.py\u001b[0m - Argument parsing logic and option handling                                                                                   \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40msrc/click/__init__.py\u001b[0m - Public API exports and main entry points                                                                                   \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40mexamples/validation/validation.py\u001b[0m - Shows parameter validation patterns                                                                            \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40mexamples/complex/complex/cli.py\u001b[0m - Advanced patterns: custom groups and dynamic commands                                                            \r\n\r\n\u001b[4;35mKey patterns and conventions\u001b[0m                                                                                                                          \r\n\r\n\u001b[1mDecorator Composition\u001b[0m: Commands are built by stacking decorators:                                                                                     \r\n\r\n\u001b[48;5;235m                                                                                                                                                      \u001b[0m\r\n"]
[101.005874, "o", "\u001b[48;5;235m \u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;148;48;5;235m@click\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;204;48;5;235m.\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;231;48;5;235mcommand\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;231;48;5;235m(\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;231;48;5;235m)\u001b[0m\u001b[48;5;235m                                                                                                                                    \u001b[0m\u001b[48;5;235m \u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[48;5;235m \u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;148;48;5;235m@click\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;204;48;5;235m.\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;231;48;5;235moption\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;231;48;5;235m(\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;186;48;5;235m'\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;186;48;5;235m--count\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;186;48;5;235m'\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;231;48;5;235m,\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;231;48;5;235m \u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;231;48;5;235mdefault\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;204;48;5;235m=\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;141;48;5;235m1\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;231;48;5;235m)\u001b[0m\u001b[48;5;235m                                                                                                                 \u001b[0m\u001b[48;5;235m \u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[48;5;235m \u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;81;48;5;235mdef\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;231;48;5;235m \u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;148;48;5;235mmycommand\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;231;48;5;235m(\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;231;48;5;235mcount\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;231;48;5;235m)\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;231;48;5;235m:\u001b[0m\u001b[48;5;235m                                                                                                                               \u001b[0m\u001b[48;5;235m \u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[48;5;235m \u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;231;48;5;235m    \u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;81;48;5;235mpass\u001b[0m\u001b[48;5;235m                                                                                                                                            \u001b[0m\u001b[48;5;235m \u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[48;5;235m                                                                                                                                                      \u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[1mContext Passing\u001b[0m: Use \u001b[1;36;40m@click.pass_context\u001b[0m or custom decorators like \u001b[1;36;40mpass_environment\u001b[0m to share state between commands.                                  \r\n\r\n\u001b[1mCustom Parameter Types\u001b[0m: Extend \u001b[1;36;40mclick.ParamType\u001b[0m for domain-specific validation (like the URL type in validation example).                              \r\n\r\n\u001b[1mDynamic Command Loading\u001b[0m: Complex applications can dynamically discover commands by implementing custom \u001b[1;36;40mGroup\u001b[0m classes with \u001b[1;36;40mlist_commands()\u001b[0m and         \r\n\u001b[1;36;40mget_command()\u001b[0m methods.                                                                                                                                \r\n\r\n\u001b[1mEnvironment Variable Integration\u001b[0m: Automatic mapping with \u001b[1;36;40mauto_envvar_prefix\u001b[0m setting.                                                                  \r\n\r\n\u001b[1mCallback Validation\u001b[0m: Use callback functions for complex parameter validation beyond types.                                                            \r\n\r\n\u001b[4;35mWhat is undocumented or surprising\u001b[0m                                                                                                                    \r\n\r\n\u001b[1mDynamic Command Discovery\u001b[0m: The complex example shows how to build plugin-style CLIs that auto-discover commands from filesystem structure (\u001b[1;36;40mcmd_*.py\u001b[0m   \r\nfiles), but this pattern isn't obvious from basic usage.                                                                                              \r\n\r\n\u001b[1mContext Settings Propagation\u001b[0m: \u001b[1;36;40mCONTEXT_SETTINGS\u001b[0m can be used to configure behavior globally, but the relationship between context settings and command  \r\nexecution isn't immediately clear.                                                                                                                    \r\n\r\n\u001b[1mCustom Group Classes\u001b[0m: You can completely override command resolution by subclassing \u001b[1;36;40mGroup\u001b[0m - this enables sophisticated CLI architectures but requires \r\nunderstanding the internals.                                                                                                                          \r\n\r\n\u001b[1mPass Decorator Factory\u001b[0m: \u001b[1;36;40mclick.make_pass_decorator()\u001b[0m creates custom context-passing decorators, allowing clean dependency injection patterns in CLI    \r\napplications.                                                                                                                                         \r\n\r\n\u001b[1mParameter Type Inheritance\u001b[0m: Custom types have access to the full parsing context, enabling sophisticated validation that depends on other parameters  \r\nor global state.                                                                                                                                      \r\n\r\n\u001b[4;35mWhere to go next\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                      \r\n\r\n\u001b[36m 1 \u001b[0m\u001b[1mStart Simple\u001b[0m: Read \u001b[1;36;40mexamples/validation/validation.py\u001b[0m to understand basic parameter handling                                                        \r\n\u001b[36m 2 \u001b[0m\u001b[1mStudy Core Classes\u001b[0m: Focus on \u001b[1;36;40msrc/click/core.py\u001b[0m to understand the object model                                                                      \r\n\u001b[36m 3 \u001b[0m\u001b[1mAdvanced Patterns\u001b[0m: Examine \u001b[1;36;40mexamples/complex/\u001b[0m for multi-command applications                                                                        \r\n\u001b[36m 4 \u001b[0m\u001b[1mCustom Types\u001b[0m: Look at \u001b[1;36;40msrc/click/types.py\u001b[0m for parameter validation patterns                                                                         \r\n\u001b[36m 5 \u001b[0m\u001b[1mTesting Approach\u001b[0m: Check \u001b[1;36;40mtests/\u001b[0m directory for testing CLI applications with Click                                                                   \r\n\u001b[36m 6 \u001b[0m\u001b[1mIntegration Patterns\u001b[0m: Explore how Click integrates with other tools (setuptools entry points, etc.)                                                \r\n\r\nThe codebase is well-structured with clear separation between core functionality, decorators, and utilities. The examples provide excellent real-world\r\nusage patterns that aren't covered in typical documentation.                                                                                          \r\n\r\n\u001b[4;35mREADME vs reality\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                     \r\n\r\n\u001b[1;35mWhat the source code reveals that the README doesn't mention\u001b[0m                                                                                          \r\n\r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mDynamic command discovery system\u001b[0m: The codebase includes sophisticated patterns for auto-discovering commands from filesystem structure (\u001b[1;36;40mcmd_*.py\u001b[0m   \r\n\u001b[1m   \u001b[0mfiles) and building plugin-style CLIs through custom \u001b[1;36;40mGroup\u001b[0m classes with \u001b[1;36;40mlist_commands()\u001b[0m and \u001b[1;36;40mget_command()\u001b[0m methods                                  \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mContext system for state management\u001b[0m: \u001b[1;36;40mContext\u001b[0m objects and decorators like \u001b[1;36;40m@click.pass_context\u001b[0m provide a complete dependency injection system for    \r\n\u001b[1m   \u001b[0msharing state between commands, but this isn't shown in the basic example                                                                          \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mCustom parameter type system\u001b[0m: \u001b[1;36;40msrc/click/types.py\u001b[0m reveals an extensible type validation framework where you can subclass \u001b[1;36;40mParamType\u001b[0m for              \r\n\u001b[1m   \u001b[0mdomain-specific validation, going far beyond basic string/int handling                                                                             \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mEnvironment variable integration\u001b[0m: Built-in \u001b[1;36;40mauto_envvar_prefix\u001b[0m setting automatically maps CLI options to environment variables, a major feature     \r\n\u001b[1m   \u001b[0mcompletely absent from the README                                                                                                                  \r\n\r\n\u001b[1;35mWhat the README oversimplifies or skips\u001b[0m                                                                                                               \r\n\r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1m\"As little code as necessary\" claim vs complex examples\u001b[0m: While the README shows a 10-line hello world, the \u001b[1;36;40mexamples/complex/\u001b[0m directory reveals that\r\n\u001b[1m   \u001b[0mreal-world CLI applications require understanding custom groups, context passing, callback validation, and sophisticated command resolution        \r\n\u001b[1m   \u001b[0mpatterns                                                                                                                                           \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1m\"Arbitrary nesting\" without implementation details\u001b[0m: The README mentions command nesting but doesn't explain that this requires understanding \u001b[1;36;40mGroup\u001b[0m \r\n\u001b[1m   \u001b[0mclasses, command registration, and the relationship between \u001b[1;36;40m@click.group()\u001b[0m and \u001b[1;36;40m@click.command()\u001b[0m decorators                                         \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mMissing testing guidance\u001b[0m: The README doesn't mention that Click provides specific testing utilities and patterns (visible in \u001b[1;36;40mtests/\u001b[0m directory) for \r\n\u001b[1m   \u001b[0mtesting CLI applications, which is crucial for any serious CLI development                                                                         \r\n"]
[101.022268, "o", "\r\n\u001b[32mSaved to \u001b[0m\u001b[32m/tmp/\u001b[0m\u001b[32mdemo-out.md\u001b[0m\r\n"]
